{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17486712","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17486712"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:42:17+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:42:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"161"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"161","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/161"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.62,0.06,0.06,0.11,0.15]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"161"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101191"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"161","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/161"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"161"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83628"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"6"},{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"217"},{"type":"tags","id":"3320"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"6275"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7354"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7431"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22085"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34724"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101191","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/101191"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 81-year-old female is admitted to hospital following recurrent falls at home. Her daughter is concerned about her level of cognitive impairment which worsened 3 months ago. She has concerns about her mother\u0027s slowness to respond to questions, inattention, and inability to complete simple tasks such as using the telephone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHer medical history includes hypertension, hyperlipidaemia, type 2 diabetes mellitus, chronic kidney disease stage 4, previous coronary artery bypass graft, obstructive sleep apnoea (not adherent to CPAP), and osteoarthritis. Her medications include perindopril, amlodipine, bisoprolol, spironolactone, prazosin, rosuvastatin, ezetimibe, metformin, semaglutide, insulin, and aspirin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination the patient is tearful and distressed as she \u0027wants to go home\u0027. She believes she is \u0027at a stranger\u0027s house\u0027 and that the year is \u00271940\u0027. She is oriented the day of the week. Vital signs are: RR 16, SpO2 96% on RA, BP 160/95, HR 82, T 37. Cardiovascular examination reveals a displaced apex beat, dual heart sounds with a systolic murmur. Respiratory examination is unremarkable. Neurological examination reveals spasticity of her left lower limb with bilateral lower limb glove and stocking sensory neuropathy. She has one small heel ulcer that appears non-infected. Vascular examination reveals absent peripheral pulses bilaterally.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EComplete blood examination is unremarkable. EUC reveals creatinine of 250 with normal sodium and potassium. HbA1c is 9%. Urinalysis reveals + proteinuria with no blood and no leukocytes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHer MRI brain is shown (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Vascular dementia","Frontotemporal dementia","Lewy body dementia","Alzheimer\u0027s disease","Mixed dementia"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient most likely has \u003Cstrong\u003Evascular dementia \u003C/strong\u003Ewhich is supported by the MRI features of small vessel disease with white matter hyperintensities, indicative of ischaemic changes. This is on the background of multiple risk factors for cerebrovascular disease. Focal neurological signs (e.g. her left leg spasticity) is also supportive of vascular dementia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMixed dementia\u003C/strong\u003E remains an alternative possibility, but the above MRI is most consistent with vascular dementia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPatients with \u003Cstrong\u003ELewy body dementia \u003C/strong\u003Eoften have fluctuating cognition and attention, motor features consistent with Parkinsonism (e.g. bradykinesia or rigidity), visual hallucinations or REM sleep behaviour disorder.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPatients with \u003Cstrong\u003Efrontotemporal dementia \u003C/strong\u003Etend to have preserved memory and instead problems with personality change, behavioural change, or speech.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPatients with \u003Cstrong\u003EAlzheimer disease \u003C/strong\u003Epresents with insidious onset and progressive memory impairment over course of six months.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["There is no one investigation that is the \u0022gold standard\u0022 for dementia, diagnosis is made by synthesising all relevant findings","Vascular dementia should be considered in patients presenting with history of cognitive decline with a background of extensive vascular risk factors"],"references":["Falk N, Cole A, Meredith TJ. Evaluation of Suspected Dementia. Am Fam Physician. 2018 Mar 15;97(6):398-405. PMID: 29671539.","Korczyn AD, Vakhapova V, Grinberg LT. Vascular dementia. J Neurol Sci. 2012 Nov 15;322(1-2):2-10. doi: 10.1016/j.jns.2012.03.027. Epub 2012 May 8. PMID: 22575403; PMCID: PMC3435447.","O\u0027Brien JT, Thomas A. Vascular dementia. Lancet. 2015 Oct 24;386(10004):1698-706. doi: 10.1016/S0140-6736(15)00463-8. PMID: 26595643."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83628"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"161"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18450"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18450","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18450"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/9614a449-3636-4973-b7e1-9307d698be8e.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/9614a449-3636-4973-b7e1-9307d698be8e.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":600}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83628","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/83628"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-30T22:52:37+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-30T22:52:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"161"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101191"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"6","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/6"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc75","name":"Geriatrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"